Here's an example code in MATLAB for using the ARIMA method for time series forecasting:

```MATLAB
% Load the data
data = load('temperature_data.mat');
Y = data.temperature;

% Define the model
model = arima(1,1,1); % p=1, d=1, q=1

% Fit the model to the data
estmodel = estimate(model, Y);

% Forecast 38 years ahead
Y_Forecast = forecast(estmodel, 38);

% Plot the results
figure;
plot(Y);
hold on;
plot(length(Y)+1:length(Y)+38, Y_Forecast, 'r--');
xlabel('Year');
ylabel('Temperature');
legend('Historical Data', 'Forecast', 'Location', 'best');
title('ARIMA Forecast for Temperature Data');
```

This code loads temperature data from a MATLAB `.mat` file, defines an ARIMA(1,1,1) model, fits the model to the data using the `estimate` function, forecasts 38 years ahead using the `forecast` function, and plots the historical data and forecast.

I see you have not provided any specific data, but if you have a dataset for the highest temperature of each year for the past 71 years, then you can use the ARIMA method for time series forecasting.

First, you need to load your data into MATLAB, you can do that in many ways, for example, if you have the data stored in a CSV file, you can use the `csvread` function to read the data into a matrix:

```MATLAB
data = csvread('temperature_data.csv');
```

Then you need to create an `arima` model using the `arima` function. The `arima` function takes three integer parameters `p, d, q` that specify the order of the ARIMA model.

```MATLAB
model = arima(p, d, q);
```

You can use the `estimate` function to estimate the model parameters from your data:

```MATLAB
estModel = estimate(model, data);
```

Finally, you can use the `forecast` function to predict the temperature for the next 38 years:

```MATLAB
forecastedData = forecast(estModel, 38);
```

You can then plot your historical data along with the forecast values using the `plot` function:

```MATLAB
plot(data);
hold on;
plot(forecastedData);
legend('Historical data', 'Forecasted data');
xlabel('Year');
ylabel('Temperature');
``` 

This is only a basic example, and there are many other parameters and techniques you may need to consider based on your specific dataset and model. It's important to be familiar with the ARIMA model and its assumptions before using it for forecasting.

