To test different ARIMA models and select the best one, you can use a combination of the `arima` function and the `estimate` function. The `arima` function can define multiple models with different parameter combinations, and the `estimate` function can estimate the model parameters and return an AIC (Akaike Information Criterion) value, which is a measure of the model's goodness-of-fit. Lower AIC values indicate better fit.

Here's an example code that defines several ARIMA models with different combinations of the parameter values `p`, `d`, and `q`. The code estimates the parameters of each model using the `estimate` function, and stores the AIC value for each model. At the end, it selects the model with the lowest AIC value:

```MATLAB
% Load the data
load Month_data\Data_Temp.mat
Y = Data;

% Define candidate models
p = 0:3; % Order of AR (AutoRegressive) process
d = 0:1; % Degree of differencing
q = 0:3; % Order of MA (Moving Average) process
models = cell(length(p)*length(d)*length(q), 1);
count = 0;
for ii = 1:length(p)
    for jj = 1:length(d)
        for kk = 1:length(q)
            count = count + 1;
            models{count} = arima(p(ii), d(jj), q(kk));
        end
    end
end

% Estimate each model and determine its AIC value
aic = zeros(length(models), 1);
for ii = 1:length(models)
    estmodel = estimate(models{ii}, Y);
    aic(ii) = estmodel.AIC;
end

% Find the model with the lowest AIC value
[minAIC,index] = min(aic);
bestModel = models{index};

% Forecast
horizon = 38;
Y_Forecast = forecast(bestModel, horizon);

% Plot the forecast
figure;
plot(Y);
hold on;
plot(length(Y)+1:length(Y)+horizon, Y_Forecast, 'r--');
xlabel('Year');
ylabel('Average Temperature (C)');
legend('Historical Data', 'ARIMA Forecast', 'Location', 'best');
title('ARIMA Forecast for Temperature Data');
```

This code defines 64 candidate models by looping over different combinations of `p`, `d`, and `q` values. Then it estimates the parameters for each model using the `estimate` function, calculates the AIC value, and selects the model with the lowest AIC. Finally, it predicts the future values and plots the forecast along with the historical data.

Note that this is a basic example, and there could be other factors affecting the model selection process, and additional analysis may be required before making a final decision on the model.

